{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510040"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:23:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:23:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11483"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11483"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.11,0.05,0.08,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4114"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110223"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4114"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11483"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92494"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1598"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5003"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6177"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34955"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41443"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110223"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of malaise and fatigue throughout the day. Over the past week, he has noticed new rashes on his feet and palms and has been experiencing excessive hair loss. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. There is no history of weight loss, changes in bowel habits, or urinary symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Cutaneous examination reveals patchy alopecia. There is a non-pruritic maculopapular reddish-brown rash on the palmoplantar surfaces, with annular rings of scale surrounding the lesions (Image). A few lymph nodes in the axillary and cervical regions are palpable with no tenderness upon palpation. Rectal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Full blood count and blood film","Lymph node fine needle aspiration","Urine nucleic acid amplification test","Skin biopsy","Syphilis serology"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of secondary syphilis, including generalised malaise, non-tender lymphadenopathy, patchy alopecia, and most importantly, a characteristic maculopapular rash on the palmoplantar surfaces with annular rings of scale. The palmoplantar distribution is particularly suggestive of syphilis, as few other conditions cause rashes in these locations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESyphilis serology\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial diagnostic test. This typically includes both non-treponemal tests (RPR or VDRL) and treponemal-specific tests (TPPA or FTA-ABS). Early diagnosis and treatment with benzathine penicillin is crucial to prevent progression to tertiary syphilis. Additional sexually transmitted infection screening, including HIV and hepatitis B/C, should also be performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFull blood count and blood film\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful to investigate causes of fatigue and lymphadenopathy such as haematological malignancies. However, the characteristic rash pattern makes syphilis the most likely diagnosis requiring immediate investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymph node fine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered for persistent lymphadenopathy to exclude lymphoma or other malignancies. However, in this clinical context with the pathognomonic rash, it is not the most appropriate initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine nucleic acid amplification test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose gonorrhoea and chlamydia. While sexual health screening is important in this patient, these infections do not cause the palmoplantar rash seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E might show non-specific inflammatory changes in secondary syphilis but is not diagnostic. It would be more appropriate for suspected malignancy or other dermatological conditions where the diagnosis is unclear.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Secondary syphilis presents with generalised non-tender lymphadenopathy, malaise, and a non-pruritic maculopapular rash on palmoplantar surfaces.","A maculopapular rash on palmoplantar surfaces with annular rings of scale is a hallmark sign of secondary syphilis.","Syphilis serology is the most appropriate initial diagnostic test when secondary syphilis is suspected."],"references":["ASHM Organisation. Syphilis - Australian STI Management Guidelines [Internet]. Australian STI management Guidelines for Use in Primary Care:2018 [cited 6 January 2022]. Available from: http://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/syphilis#clinical-presentation","Nyatsanza F, Tipple C. Syphilis: presentations in general medicine. Clinical Medicine. 2016 Apr;16(2):184 [Cited 6 January 2022}. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4952975/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92494"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11483"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20167"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20167"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7e55ddb3-bc93-498c-aab0-44e5a6c783db.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7e55ddb3-bc93-498c-aab0-44e5a6c783db.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":305,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92494"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-29T09:44:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T09:45:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4114"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110223"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":nul